                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1123 Lincheng/108: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-05-28T16:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 28, 1923—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 28—9:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>185. My 179, May 24, 5 p.m. Telegram from Lincheng May 27, 2 a.m., reports that
                    brigands replied in polite tone and stated that they would do nothing to
                    endanger lives of foreigners and that they would accept reasonable conditions if
                    Chinese Government would offer them. Brigands reiterated their five demands.</p>
                <p>Powell returned to Tsaochuang May 27, 6 p.m., with two bandit secretaries, whose
                    safe conduct he guaranteed. This forenoon secretaries were conferring with
                    Assistant Military Governor.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
